	abstract = {UNLABELLED: The vertebrate intestine is home to microbial\${\textbackslash}backslash\$necosystems that play key roles in host development and health.\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nLittle is known about the spatial and temporal dynamics of\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nthese microbial communities, limiting our understanding of\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nfundamental properties, such as their mechanisms of growth,\${\textbackslash}backslash\$npropagation, and persistence. To address this, we inoculated\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ninitially germ-free zebrafish larvae with fluorescently\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nlabeled strains of an Aeromonas species, representing an\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nabundant genus in the zebrafish gut. Using light sheet\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nfluorescence microscopy to obtain three-dimensional images\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nspanning the gut, we quantified the entire bacterial load, as\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nfounding populations grew from tens to tens of thousands of\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ncells over several hours. The data yield the first ever\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nmeasurements of the growth kinetics of a microbial species\${\textbackslash}backslash\$ninside a live vertebrate intestine and show dynamics that\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nrobustly fit a logistic growth model. Intriguingly, bacteria\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nwere nonuniformly distributed throughout the gut, and\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nbacterial aggregates showed considerably higher growth rates\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nthan did discrete individuals. The form of aggregate growth\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nindicates intrinsically higher division rates for clustered\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nbacteria, rather than surface-mediated agglomeration onto\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nclusters. Thus, the spatial organization of gut bacteria both\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nrelative to the host and to each other impacts overall growth\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nkinetics, suggesting that spatial characterizations will be an\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nimportant input to predictive models of host-associated\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nmicrobial community assembly. IMPORTANCE: Our intestines are\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nhome to vast numbers of microbes that influence many aspects\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nof health and disease. Though we now know a great deal about\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nthe constituents of the gut microbiota, we understand very\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nlittle about their spatial structure and temporal dynamics in\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nhumans or in any animal: how microbial populations establish\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nthemselves, grow, fluctuate, and persist. To address this, we\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nmade use of a model organism, the zebrafish, and a new optical\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nimaging technique, light sheet fluorescence microscopy, to\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nvisualize for the first time the colonization of a live,\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nvertebrate gut by specific bacteria with sufficient resolution\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nto quantify the population over a range from a few individuals\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nto tens of thousands of bacterial cells. Our results provide\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nunprecedented measures of bacterial growth kinetics and also\${\textbackslash}backslash\$nshow the influence of spatial structure on bacterial\${\textbackslash}backslash\$npopulations, which can be revealed only by direct imaging.},
